International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 13 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet, 12 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-10/13/content_2083494.htm>

Foot and mouth disease outbreaks in western Uganda
-----------------------------------------------
Following the outbreak of foot and mouth disease in Kigoyera parish,
in the sub-county of Kyarusozi, western Uganda, quarantine
restrictions are imposed on the sub-county, Radio Uganda reported on
Tuesday [12 Oct 2004].
On Tue 12 Oct 2004, Kyenjojo's district livestock health and
entomology official, Dr. C. Rutebarika, announced that transportation
from, to, and within the sub-county of all livestock, livestock
products, and by-products would be prohibited immediately until
further notice. Rutebarika said that all livestock markets in the
sub-county of Kyarusozi have been closed. He also requested
veterinary staff, local councils, chiefs, enforcement personnel, and
the general public in neighboring areas to enforce quarantine
restrictions so that the disease is brought under control. He added
that district veterinary officials of the surrounding districts of
Bundibugyo, Kaborole, Kibale, and Hoima had been informed accordingly.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[35 outbreaks of FMD have been officially reported by Uganda to the
OIE during 2003; no information has been forthcoming during 2004.
Official confirmation of FMD in Kyarusozi (Kyenjojo District),
including details on the involved serotype, will be helpful. -
Mod.AS].
